                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/llcu-300" class="program-course-title">
              LLCU 300 Cinema and the Visual (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-29370" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Languages, Literatures and Cultures (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/607">Faculty of Arts</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      LLCU              : This seminar examines topics in European and/or transatlantic cinema and visual culture, including film theory, aesthetics and historiography; media archeology; cinema and the digital; film and philosophy; cultural histories of the cinema; and approaches to moving images.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Fall 2014          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Michael Cowan (Fall)                  </p>

    
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/muhl-330" class="program-course-title">
              MUHL 330 Music and Film (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-31122" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Music Research (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/613">Schulich School of Music</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Music History and Literature              : The modern genre of music for films, and its changing styles (symphonic, jazz, pop compilation) from the silent era to today. Includes study of major film composers in North America and other traditions; analysis of the role of music in cinematic narrative, expression and symbolism.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Fall 2014          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Lloyd Whitesell (Fall)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Prerequisites: MUHL 184 and MUHL 185 and MUTH 211 OR MUCO 240D1/D2 and MUSP 231 OR MUHL 286 and MUTH 250 and MUSP 241</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/plai-500" class="program-course-title">
              PLAI 500 Advanced Interdisciplinary Humanities Seminar (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-33725" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Inst Public Life-Arts &amp; Ideas (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/607">Faculty of Arts</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      PLAI              : Co-taught seminar will use and explore a range of theoretical and methodological approaches to interdisciplinary research in the humanities in the study of a selected cultural problem or topic, text, artwork, aesthetic or medium.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Winter 2015          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Jui Ramaprasad, Bronwen Low (Winter)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Prerequisite: Minimum U3 status with a background in humanities scholarship</li>
              <li>See <a href="http://www.mcgill.ca/iplai/courses/" title="http://www.mcgill.ca/iplai/courses/" rel="nofollow">http://www.mcgill.ca/iplai/courses/</a> for details on current teaching faculty and course topics.</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
                </ul>
      
      
